Carabinero Prawns. Jumbo and juicy, these prawns are caught off the coast of Huelva, in southwestern Spain.⁠
⁠
Carabineros are the world's largest prawns, traditionally prepared in Spanish and Portuguese cuisines with a bit of salt and a few minutes on the grill, showcasing their rich sweetness. ⁠
⁠
We also love them seared, poached, or steamed, dressed with nori butter to coax out an even creamier mouthfeel.⁠
⁠
Don't let any bit go to waste—so much of their distinctive flavor is in the head, which retains its brilliantly red color throughout the cooking process.⁠

Freshly harvested from France, we are thrilled to now offer these Périgords alongside our still-sensational White Truffles and late-season Burgundy Truffles as well.⁠

Texas Wagyu Tri-Tip Au Poivre with foraged Black Trumpets.

Tri-Tip is a tender, toothsome cut from the bottom sirloin, loaded with an iconic fat cap that binds beautifully with these smoky, aromatic mushrooms foraged in the Pacific Northwest.

King Crab Crêpe with mung bean, Thai basil, and trout roe.

King Crabs are massive, formidably clawed, and ten-legged, with a majestic presence that perfectly suits the name. This spring, we have live Norwegian Red Kings as well as frozen leg clusters, both of which present a multitude of uses in the kitchen.

Shown here in a light, bright recipe that plays their sweetness against the brisk pop of Trout roe, we love seeing creative dishes with such regal centerpieces.

Frog Legs Meunière with Capers & Browned Butter

Hand-caught in Louisiana, these frog legs are pure and fresh as any to be found in the US. With a plump texture and a flavor profile that straddles the line between poultry and fish, they’re a sneakily excellent crowd-pleaser, especially when breaded, deep-fried, and garnished with late-season Black Périgord truffles.

Baked Moon Snails with Herbs, Garlic Butter, and Caviar 

Like many saltwater snails, Atlantic Moons feast on slow-moving prey like clams, imparting a superb flavor all their own. 

Sourced as bycatch from New England fisheries, these are far fresher than readily available renditions of the trio of Eurasian snails typically used for escargot, and can be used quite similarly. Here, with Platinum Osetra caviar and fresh herbs, we’re leaning into the brisk sweetness of early spring by the sea.

Wagyu Inside Skirt with Shoyu Yolk Dipping Sauce

Intensely juicy and lean enough to love a quick sear or short stint on the grill, our American Wagyu Inside Skirt is a gorgeous cut to pair with an umami-rich dipping sauce like this one.

Small enough to be enjoyed in one bite, the yolk and quail of these Balut eggs have a soft, creamy texture that's similar to perfect poached chicken soup, and are often complemented by some citrus and any tangy or spicy accoutrements that you may have on hand. Our favorite aromatics for the occasion are Vietnamese cilantro, garlic, lemon, salt, pepper, and fish sauce, all whipped together into a lively dressing.

Balut eggs are beloved throughout Southeast Asia, where they are frequently sold as street food and known as Trứng Cút Lộn. Though distinctions exist across cultures, they are typically fertilized duck eggs, incubated for two to three weeks, that are then boiled, steamed, and eaten directly from the shell. We prefer these Quail eggs, however, sourced from one of the most principled and distinguished Quail farms in the country.

When the pandemic initially hit, this farm was faced with the sudden disappearance of the vast majority of their buyers, with countless birds still in line to be hatched and harvested. By pivoting a considerable amount of their operation toward Balut production and export, they were not only able to sustain their business, but they avoided eggs or birds going to waste, and prevented unsustainable overpopulation on the farm.

Spring is officially springing.

This White Asparagus Tart with trout roe and crème fraîche packs the color, freshness, and pop that mark the best of this season.

Jumbo White Asparagus is an entirely different vegetable from the traditional, skinny, green stuff commonplace in the United States. Aside from its snowy color, this French variety is significantly larger, sweeter, more tender, and appropriately revered in European markets and kitchens.

Firefly Squid (Hotaru Ika ホタルイカ) get their name for the vibrant blue glow they brandish during spawning season—an enchanting sight that heralds springtime in Japan.

Their taste is bold, briny, and not too fishy, most commonly compared to rich, fatty shrimp. Regardless of how they’re prepared, we highly recommend eating them whole, as the mix of textures contained within just one bite is absolutely one of a kind.

Wild Spring Greens are beginning to trickle in from the warmer temperate pockets of the US, and we’re poised to make the most of ‘em.

Here we have three-cornered leeks—a flowering spring onion also sometimes nicknamed “snowbell”—paired with Maitake and A5 Wagyu from the Kagoshima prefecture in Japan.

Tender stems, crisp leaves, and crunchy buds and bulbs make every bit of this spicy, garlicky allium a winner. Swipe to see them all on their own, and swipe again to damn near smell the flowers.

Poached Provençal White Asparagus with chives and caviar béarnaise. A crisp, bright dish for any springtime occasion.

With sweeter flavor and softer texture than traditional varieties, White Asparagus hugely rewards gentle preparations like this one.
Here’s one for all the egg hunters out there. Guess it’s not so surprising that we happened to find ours alongside flaky sea salt and Black Truffles 🤷‍♂️

Hiramasa, or Yellowtail Kingfish, is a large, fatty, and fittingly regal catch that’s tremendously popular in Japan.

Exceedingly rare to come upon in the open sea, our Hiramasa is sustainably farmed in Australia. Averaging close to 10 lbs, and with a superbly generous ratio of meat to bone, it makes for an epic option for whole-roasting, though sashimi is perhaps its most prominent claim to fame.

Now available online.

Charred Firefly Squid Nigiri.

As springtime gets sweeter and sweeter in our neck(s) of the woods, we’re also channeling the season’s hallmarks across the Pacific.

In this dish, American-made Shoyu complements the pair of centerpieces from Japan—squid and toasted nori.

Thick cut, maple glazed Mangalitsa Bacon on a buttermilk biscuit.

We can’t be certain, but odds are you deserve an epic brunch biscuit for the weekend. 

Mangalitsa is a Hungarian Heritage pig breed known for its abundant good fat and rich, steak-like flavor. Ours is a cross between Mangalitsa and Berkshire, carefully raised and selected over several generations by our partner in Iowa. The meat is deep red, intricately marbled, and loaded with unbelievably complex and satisfying flavor.

These ruby red Carabinero Prawns are consistently among our favorite centerpieces. Now, with the weather warming and daylight stretching, we’re thinking of this charred Carabinero dish with tangerine vinegar and ikura roe.

Caught off the coast of southwestern Spain, these prawns are flash frozen at sea, maximizing their longevity and retaining their fresh, vibrant flavor all the way to the grill.

Wild Ramp Caramelle

For foragers, finding the right pocket of woods in the springtime can feel like being a kid in a candy store, and this stuffed pasta dish drives that point home beautifully.

Of all the wild greens that signal the arrival of springtime, few have as avid a fanbase as ramps. With flavors reminiscent of shallots, leeks, and wild garlic, what sets ramps apart is that they evoke these piquant alliums while staying sweeter, mellower, and more palatably balanced, whether raw or cooked.

This time of year, we’ll put ramps on just about anything, but with parm fonduta and this playful pasta shape, spring feels especially triumphant.

Tap above to snag some clean wild ramps while their season lasts.

This week, we’ll be offering some stellar deals on favorite caviars throughout our collection. As always, newsletter subscribers hear about it first, so visit our website (link in bio!) to sign up and get in on the action.

After all, springtime’s as swell a season as any for epic snack plates and classic caviar service 😎

Claytonia Perfoliata earned the nickname “Miner’s Lettuce” during the Gold Rush, when miners throughout the American West foraged and ate as much of this wild green as they could. And long before these newcomers plucked the leaves plucked from the ground, Indigenous Americans often boiled the whole plant, as its leaves are sturdy and flavorful.

Thanks to its ample supplies of iron and Vitamins A & C, Claytonia was a refreshing scurvy repellent for its eponymous 19th-century adopters, but thankfully, today we can just focus on its mild, elegant flavor and crunchy texture. And unlike many other greens, Claytonia retains its crisp and mellow flavor even when in bloom, making the whole handsome plant both edible and delicious.

Firefly Squid Tempura with Spring Onion Aioli

This dish celebrates some of our favorite signs of springtime both here at home and abroad in Japan. Our Hotaru Ika is fresh, delicious, and fried to perfection alongside an aioli spiked with ramps and wild spring onions. Altogether, this dish delivers crisp textures and bright flavors in a stunning snapshot of the season.

All of these key ingredients are in stock while their short, sweet seasons sustain.

Spring things.

With white asparagus, wild ramps, ramp oil, fresh peas, and a perfectly poached egg, this dish is everything we look for in a spring salad.

Tap the photo to snag these ingredients, and keep 👀 on your inbox for this simple recipe if you’re a subscriber 😉

Ibérico Pork McRib

This is a wildly satisfying homage to the classic McRib, featuring Ibérico pork with Strawberry Gochujang on a warm Brioche bun. 

Ibérico Spare Ribs are one of our favorite pork selections for the grill, and this strawberry-spiked chili paste lends a distinctly sweet and tart counterpoint to the sandwich’s richness.

Grilling season is underway, folks. We’re here to help 🔥

Crispy Acadian Redfish with Cucumber and Roe

Springtime Redfish from the Gulf of Maine are sweet, smooth, and perfectly proportioned for a huge variety of dishes. Garnished with roe and a fresh, crunchy green, this simple dish shines across the board.

Our Redfish are caught on one of the few hook-and-line boats still operating along this stretch of the New England coast, and the quality of every catch showcases the discipline and talent required to sustain this sort of operation.

Sawagani Tostada with Ramps and Spring Onions

These Japanese freshwater crabs are about the size of a potato chip, and when fried, are delightfully similar in texture. Their flavor is fresh and crisp, like a concentrated soft shelled crab, and when gobbled up in one bite, the exterior crunch of the shell juxtaposes against the buttery, unctuous interior in a way that’s downright magical.

Paired with vibrant flowering three-cornered leeks and wild ramps, this is a perfect springtime spread.

Head online to snag your spring greens while their seasons last and pre-order Sawagani fresh from Japan.

Ramp Pancakes with Shoyu

Truly no shortage of ramp inspiration over here. This spin on classic scallion pancakes puts one of our favorite wild spring greens to glorious use once again, with all the gloss, shimmer, and crunch you know and love. Served with our American-made Shoyu as a simple dipping sauce.

Italian Summer Black Truffles are here.

Milder and more approachable than their Winter Black Truffle cousins, these have a beautiful light hazelnut fragrance and a deep, nutty flavor. 

These really shine brightest when warmed, layered under the skin of a chicken before roasting or grated onto piping hot pasta.

Live Alaskan Percebes

AKA Gooseneck Barnacles, these wild looking shellfish are as esteemed and elusive as anything we carry. Tough to find, difficult and dangerous to harvest, and often disappointingly demure, these jumbo and juicy catches will turn anyone into an admirer. 

Revered in Iberian cuisines, Barnacles have a tender, smooth texture that is similar to razor clams, a comparison echoed in their flavor, somewhere snugly between clams and shrimp.

The rocky, frigid seascape off the Alaskan coast is owed much of the credit for how beautiful these particular selections turn out, and the rest belongs to the talented, knowledgeable fishers who astutely time their treks among the boulders to bring these Barnacles home.
Welcome to Regalis Family Meal

American Shrimp

We’re extremely excited to bring four new species of shrimp to our collection—Golden, Northern Grey, Pink Spotted, and Rock. All are sashimi-grade, with different strengths depending on how you envision using them. Golden brings firm and snappy texture that’s great for cooking, Northern Grey are light and super versatile, Pink Spotted are soft and terrific for frying, and finally, Rock may be the most unique—sold head-on, packing incredible salinity and umami.

The only way to pick a favorite is to try ‘em all 😏

Mangalitsa Carbonara

Here’s hoping all the moms out there are having something as classy and comforting as this pasta dish whipped up for them today ♥️

Ramp Risotto with Valserena Parmigiano and Beech Mushrooms

Ramp season is winding down, but there’s still time to snag enough to make something special.

Here, every bit of the ramp is put to use for a colorful and crisp risotto, made all the better with Beech Mushrooms (aka Hon Shimeji or Japanese Honey Mushrooms) and some of the finest parm you can buy, sourced from the oldest Parmigiano Reggiano dairy in Parma.

One of our favorite ingredients is back in season. Live Spot Prawn from San Clemente Island. Fantastic raw or lightly grilled. Available now.

#prawn #shrimp
Skewers for the road

Duck Capelletti en Brodo with Summer Black Truffles

We recently found a new partner for Pekin Duck, reinvigorating our enthusiasm for fine poultry dishes like these. Raised on organic pastures with room to roam freely and enjoy all of the grass and grubs scattered throughout the landscape, the quality of these birds is evident in every offering.

This dish has the Pekin Duck Legs at its core, with a deeply aromatic broth and Italian Summer Truffles shaved on top, imparting a lovely, nutty fragrance.

Rock Shrimp Crudo

With squat heads, thick shells, and iconic stripes, Rock Shrimp are unmistakable, and their distinction is driven home even further with their intense savory flavor. Naturally salty and umami with a thick snappy texture.

It’s extremely rare to see rock shrimp whole. Usually they are deshelled and marinated in a brine. Typically flavorless and a commodity product, we were thrilled to taste such an amazing domestic Gulf product. Caught on a small vessel that is part of a decade-long Fishery Improvement Project in the Gulf of Mexico.

Something that we are extremely proud to support. 

#rockshrimp #shrimp

Lady Fiddlehead Ferns

Anyone who has seen these tightly spiraled fronds can attest to their whimsical charm, but the appeal of Fiddlehead Ferns runs deeper than meets the eye. As with other wild mushrooms in our catalog, those who forage these must be diligent and experienced, making the most of their short season and distinguishing between their inedible and sometimes poisonous lookalikes.

Whether sautéed, braised, or pickled, these are a super fun veggie to mix into your springtime spread while their season lasts.

Fried Shrimp Sandwich with Slaw & Caviar

With a firm, snappy texture and refreshingly assertive minerality, Golden Shrimp is our top-choice for any prawn recipe that calls for deeper cooking. Even when fried and dressed with slaw and aioli, their flavor still shines, and their structure stays sturdy till it’s time to dig in.

Like all of our shrimp from the Gulf of Mexico, these are caught on a small vessel that is part of a decade-long Fishery Improvement Project that we are proud to support.

Conica Morels

After a long stretch of tough weather out west, we are thrilled and thankful to finally have domestic wild Morels back in full swing. These Conicas come from Oregon, Washington, and Idaho, sourced from high elevations for exceptional flavor, texture, and cleanliness.

Morels are beloved for their meaty texture, nutty flavor, and iconically honeycombed appearance. Throughout the country, different varieties pop up from spring through early summer, but these first yields from out west are always a triumph.

Chilean Winter Black Truffles

They’re almost here. As summer advances across the northern hemisphere, winter descends down south, bringing these gorgeous Périgord Black Truffles into season in Chile.

These cultivated truffles dazzle with their quality and their meticulously upheld grading system. Loaded with earthy, chocolatey, gently sweet and vividly complex flavors, these are the finest renditions we’ve tasted from the southern hemisphere.

Our first shipment will be available next week—join our mailing list to be among the first to know!

Tasmanian Murasaki Uni

Murasaki Uni is the cleanest, sweetest Uni variety, with a creamier texture and a more elegant balance of flavor than its counterpart, Bafun. This particular selection comes from an emerging powerhouse in the global uni market—Australia.

While Japanese Uni remains the gold standard around the world, Tasmanian receives ample praise for its similarity in flavor and scrumptiously plump texture. Perhaps there is no stronger proof of its quality than the fact that so much of it is exported straight to Japan, with Regalis standing as one of the few fortunate partners offering these catches in the US.

Wild Spring Porcini are one of the most recognizably beloved mushroom species in the world. This particular variety is known as Boletus Edulis, also known as the King Bolete, the Cepe in France or just simply Boletus in Italy. There are over 300 different bolete species, not all of them edible.

These were foraged in the Sierra Nevadas in California where they typically grow at the base of coniferous trees in thick mossy habitats. The most prized specimens are young and still partially submerged in the forest floor. Firmness is a sign of quality and their convex caps can vary from rusty red tones to whiteish orangey browns. As they mature, their caps flatten, their stalks darken, and they begin to get soft. Their underside pores also begin to yellow. Keeping their iconic shape intact is key but has proven itself difficult as porcini are extremely fragile. The slightest jostle will break off their cap from their stem, instantly reducing their value.

Porcini have a fantastically nutty flavor with an ever so slightly firm bite texture. They can be eaten raw which for a wild species is extremely hard to come by, or they can be sautéed or roasted whole. 

Usually the season is short and sporadic. We expect this spring’s crop to run for 2-3 weeks. 

Enjoy them while they’re here, or miss out until the autumn flush!

#porcini #mushrooms #bolete

Prawn Crudo with Chilean Black Winter Truffles & Smoked Trout Roe

Sushi-grade shrimp is a brisk, gorgeous centerpiece deserving equally exceptional finishing touches. Here, we have New Caledonia Blue Prawns with Chilean Périgord Truffles and our applewood smoked trout roe.

In addition to these Blue Prawns, our catalog is full of exquisite Gulf of Mexico shrimp these days—perfectly suited to the season. In tandem with the return of smoked trout roe—a longtime favorite collaboration of ours—it is a great time to stock up on fresh, invigorating ingredients.

social_posts.post_text:
Porcini and Truffle Sticky Rice

Brown-capped, charmingly rotund, nutty and lusciously buttery when cooked—California Sierra Porcinis might be our favorite domestic mushroom of the moment. Though Porcinis from different parts of the world come in and out of season throughout throughout the year, this springtime American flush is short and especially sweet.

With a sturdy enough texture to withstand a nice sear, this dish layers sliced Porcini with Chilean Black Truffle, herbs, egg, and flaky salt on top of soy sticky rice, altogether delivering abundant aromatics and deep umami in every bite.

Black Morel Caramelle with Parmesan Fonduta & Wild Allium Aioli

The start of summer is high time for wild mushrooms, and few have as enthusiastic a fanbase as Black Morels from the Pacific Northwest. Right now these are looking and tasting beautiful, with great structure and that signature earthy, woodsy taste that binds so splendidly with creamy sauces like this one.

An aged parm fonduta saturates this canvas of pasta, morels and wild spring onion aioli, fusing so many sensations of the seasons into an everyday comfort dish.

With supply so strong, right now we’re offering the best morel prices of the season—head online to get ‘em while they’re here!

Roasted Black Morel with Tasmanian Uni & Chilean Black Truffle

Morels of any shape and size are a treasure, but it’s especially thrilling to find jumbo picks like this one. Typically this size comes with sturdier structure to those honeycombed walls, meaning they’ll get super satisfying caramelization when roasted.

For this dish, we’ve stuffed the big boi with Tasmanian Murasaki Uni and Chilean Périgords. Murasaki is the brighter and more delicate Uni variety, making it an incredible contrast with the earthy, chocolatey truffles and the crisp, woodsy foundation of the morel.

Chilean Black Truffle Sacchetti

Sacchetti is sometimes nicknamed “Beggar’s Purse,” but when garnished with fresh winter truffles, truffle butter, and aged Parmesan, this title certainly feels like a misnomer.

Truffles and pasta are a common and beloved pairing, since the heat and fat of a fresh pasta dish are so perfectly poised to unlock and accentuate the truffle’s incredible aroma and umami.

Grilled Berkshire Pork Chop with Dijon Beurre Blanc & Smoked Trout Roe

The best grilling days of the summer are still ahead of us, and we couldn’t be more ready. For this one, we’ve got the most delicious and intense pork chop you could possibly desire, pulled from our bone-in, center-cut 8-bone Berkshire rack. Served alongside a ladleful of Dijon Beurre Blanc dotted with smoked trout roe, this one hits all the spots.

Morel, Uni, and Trout Roe Donburi

Right now, the western US is giving us an embarrassment of riches: Conica Morels from the northwest, Murasaki Uni from southern California, and smoked Steelhead Trout Roe from the Columbia River in Washington.

Laid over a bed of rice, this medley packs loads of umami without sacrificing the brisk brightness we all crave amidst these dog days of summer.

Seared Ibérico Presa with Garlic Scape, Green Tomato, and Urfa Biber Chile

This summer, we’re thrilled to introduce a range of American-raised and Portuguese-approved Puro Alentejano Ibérico—the first and only of its kind. The dedication, diligence, and resources required to make this happen are truly too vast to summarize here, but we promise that the results are proportionally thrilling and phenomenal.

Hailing from 100% Alentejo hogs imported to the US and with Ibérico seal-of-distinction standards upheld annually by Portuguese auditors, this is the real deal. The Presa cut, in particular, is exceptionally well-marbled and perfect for a rapid sear with a gentle finish in the oven.

Head online to learn more and give some a try 🔥

Saffron Cheese Grits with Blue Crystal Prawns

Sweet and succulent New Caledonia Blue Crystal Prawns make for an incredible focal point of this creative and comforting variation on Shrimp & Grits. Floral complexity from the saffron, a touch of heat from a Moromi chili butter, and the toothsome textural combo of the grits and prawns all build upon a gorgeous, aromatic foundation that we never get tired of.

A5 Kagoshima Wagyu with Platinum Osetra, Summer Truffle, and Maitake

Kagoshima is a prefecture in southern Japan, dotted with active and dormant volcanoes and a warm, tropical climate. Wagyu from here is known for its tender texture, full-bodied depth of flavor, and its even marbling consistency throughout every fiber of the muscles. 

Here, the Maitake has been seared in the Wagyu fat, doubling down on this dish’s umami foundation. Fresh and fragrant Summer Truffles plus healthy dollops of Platinum Osetra provide the brisk lift that this dish needs for balance and poise.

Chilean Black Truffle Pasta with Uni Sauce

Truffle and Uni is one of our favorite pairings—the Périgords are so powerfully rich and earthy, while the Murasaki Uni is so brisk and bright. Anchored together in a simple pasta dish, every bite here is loaded with complexity. 

Right now, Chile is producing unbelievably excellent Winter Truffles, and Southern California is flush with freshly harvested Murasaki Uni—the more delicate and floral variety, equally palatable on its own as it is weaved into a sauce, like so.

Berkshire Pork Tonkatsu with Sesame, Platinum Osetra, and Soy Reduction 

Lean and tender yet still intricately marbled, juicy, and flavorful, our Berkshire tenderloins are a perfect fit for Tonkatsu. With a house soy reduction to drive the umami base and a healthy dollop of bright and nutty Platinum Osetra, this dish hits all the spots.

European Blue Lobster. Similar to their Maine cousins but with even more concentrated and intense flavor. Sweet but more assertively briny as well. The meat is more tender, tucked beneath a thicker shell, imparting even more baseline succulence. When cooked, their color will transform back to a familiar red hue, however with intricate white speckling. 

Versatile in any raw or finished dish.

Available now. 

#bluelobster

Summer Black Truffle Udon with Smoked Trout Roe & Maitake Shoyu

Tuber Aestivum—Summer Black Truffles—are the milder cousin to Tuber Melanosporum—Winter Black Truffles. Their aroma is not as intense or pungent, their character is mellower overall, and their interior color ranges from creamy blonde to light brown.

Because of their milder presence on the palate and their lower price point, these truffles can be used liberally as a finishing touch on warm dishes, imparting hazelnutty fragrance and flavor.

With ample truffles and dollops of smoked trout roe, this Udon in a Maitake Shoyu broth is decadently loaded with flavor while never veering overboard in any direction.

Chilean Black Truffle Macaron with Dark Chocolate Ganache

It’s a summer Friday, so we’re cruising into the weekend with something sweet on our minds. And believe it or not, we really do think that these Périgords are an amazing finishing touch to dishes with decadent chocolate foundations. The truffle’s earthy, musty, chocolatey fragrance complements this macaron’s ganache while showing its added complexity primarily in the finish—a perfectly alluring balance that’s satisfying right away and truly exceptional as it resonates on the palate.

These Chilean Périgords are an incredible value compared to their European counterparts, pushing us to get even more creative with how we use them. So far, we’re yet to be disappointed.

Moulard Duck Breast with Cabbage and Afghan Pistachio

A brief reprieve from the heat has us steering toward this simple, hearty plate of duck and cabbage, rounded out with a summer berry gastrique and pistachios. With blissful tension between the savory, fatty foundation of the duck and its fat against the tart high tones of the gastrique, this dish delivers in every bite, each worth savoring.

Lobster Mushrooms are back.

These are the delicious byproduct of the carnage wreaked upon Russula and Lactarius mushrooms by a parasite called Hypomeces. Once attacked, these otherwise mild-mannered fungi contort their figure, redden their hue, and take on a striking fragrance reminiscent of—you guessed it—steamy, buttery lobster.

Their texture is robust and crunchy even when cooked, and their aroma adds incredible complexity to simple dishes. 

Swipe to see these plated with whipped farmer’s cheese, pickled onions, and an herb purée.

Finger Limes are a unique citrus variety with individual internal pearls that burst with acidity and brightness. They are the perfect textural addition to anything needing some pop and shimmer. 

Finger limes have the widest range of color variation within any citrus species, ranging from green to red to black. 

#fingerlime

Ibérico Secreto with Golden Kaluga Caviar

Secreto is a thin, juicy cut from an especially fatty section between the shoulder blade and the loin. It is among the most cherished parts of the famed Ibérico pig, and one that is wonderfully amenable to fast prep on the grill.

With its characteristically sweet and nutty flavor, this simple preparation is made all the more elegant with a heaping scoop of caviar on top, adding brisk and bright top notes to a hefty foundation.

Chanterelle White Pizza with Osetra Caviar

Chanterelles are firm, meaty, golden mushrooms that are consistently among the most fondly regarded foraged edibles we carry. Their texture makes them exceptionally versatile and resilient across myriad methods, with an earthy, peppery, piquant foundation offset by a subtly sweet brightness that reminds many of apricots.

Mushrooms are a classic pizza topping, and even on this decidedly unconventional square slice, they perfectly deliver. And as is the case with many of our dishes, the best bites of this pie are brightened up with Osetra caviar.

A5 Wagyu with Acorn Squash & Golden Chanterelles

Here we have another gorgeous dish featuring in-season Golden Chanterelles, this time alongside A5 Wagyu from Japan and a beautiful squash purée.

Chanterelles’ mix of earthiness and sweetness makes them an especially satisfying link between the deep savoriness of the beef at this dish’s center and the nutty sweetness provided by the squash purée. 

Right now, we’re happy to have A5 selections from both the Kagoshima and Miyazaki prefectures. With such astoundingly high quality to the raw beef, a simple sear is all these cuts need to shine as any dish’s centerpiece.

Golden Prawn Spring Roll with Trout Roe & Rye Shoyu 

Our lineup of Gulf Prawns has been one of our favorite collections this summer, and the Goldens are the most assertive of the bunch. Their texture is firm and snappy, with briny brightness reinforced by exceptional minerality—qualities that help it withstand deeper cooking than most American shrimp.

All of the above make this shrimp our current favorite for spring rolls. Imbued with extra bursts of complexity by smoked trout roe and rye Shoyu, this is a superb way to kick off an epic meal.

Live Geoduck

We love to see some extra attention being paid this week to an often-overlooked shellfish—Geoduck Clams. Though perhaps not the prettiest fish in the sea, these are a distinct, delicious, and invigorating selection that’s especially cherished in Chinese, Japanese, and Korean cuisines.

Sweet, zingy, and not too fishy, ours are sourced from the Pacific Northwest, where their shells can grow up to 8 inches long and their soft bodies can stretch over three feet when unfurled.

Swipe the image above to see what’s tucked beneath the shell.

Available now for pre-order.

Lobster & Beech Mushroom Toast with Summer Truffles

It continues to be an epic August for lobster mushrooms. One of the most distinct offerings in our ever-evolving and expanding collection of foraged mushrooms, these earn their name for the sweet, shellfishy fragrance and deep red color they take on when attacked by Hypomeces.

With beech mushrooms and fresh summer truffles atop a miso aioli, this is as magnificent as mushroom toast can be.

Button Chanterelle & Golden Osetra Caviar Bucatini

Simple pasta dishes are sometimes the best way to showcase sensational ingredients. With a chive and caviar butter sauce as the base, this gorgeous nest of bucatini lets these fresh European chanterelles take the lead. Their flavor is robust and round, their texture satisfyingly crisp, and their aftertaste is softly sweet.

With Golden Osetra caviar to brighten everything up, this is one we’ll have on repeat for as long as these Chanterelles are in season.

Seared Hokkaido Sea Scallops with Brown Butter & Wild Leeks

Scallops from Hokkaido are known for their explosive sweetness, vibrantly juicy texture, and impeccably delicate flavor. Though phenomenal raw, their size and plumpness make them wonderful for a hard sear, yielding a crackling exterior followed by supple smoothness on the inside.

It’s no coincidence that so many of the world’s most revered seafood selections come from the waters surrounding Japan’s northernmost prefecture. From the northeast, the island is met by the frigid Oyashio Current, bringing water southward from the Arctic Circle. Colliding with the Kuroshio Current off Japan’s eastern shores, high tides and a nutrient-rich environment form fertile ground for an abundance of flora and fauna. 

We are incredibly proud of every selection that we source from Japan, and Hokkaido in particular. These scallops are available for pre-order now.

Nitrogen Frozen Black Périgord Truffles. 

The most esteemed of all black truffle varieties with deep, earthy undertones of cognac, chocolate, and musk. Until very recently, freezing Périgords could never quite resurrect their full glory, but we are thrilled and proud to now have a process that does so.

Shave them on anything. 

#blacktruffle #truffle #liquidnitrogen

Charred Hearts of Palm with Platinum Osetra Caviar

The deliciously sweet, crunchy cores of Cabbage Palm Trees have creamy hints of coconut that go on to evoke the clean, mild earthiness of white asparagus or artichoke when cooked. Sourced from our dear partners in Hawaii, these are a phenomenal and scarcely seen vegetable in most of the country. Sturdy enough to char, as shown here, these are also lovely if thinly shaved over salads, and you can stretch their lifespan to great effect by pickling them.

This dish is a twist on one we might whip up with white asparagus in the springtime—grilled and laid over an herb oil base, dappled with caviar, dill, and chamomile to add brightness and aromatic intrigue.

Hearts of Palm are in season and available now.

King Crab Roll with Chilean Black Winter Truffle

Through n’ through, this one’s a real winner. Poached Norwegian King Crab tossed in Nori butter with globs of Osetra caviar on a buttered potato roll, finished with the last fresh Black Chilean Périgord truffles of the season. It’s decadent in the best of ways—scrumptious, bright, and satiating. 

Our peerless selection of live seafood can be intimidating to some home cooks, but keeping eyes on a prize like this is a great motivator to give it a try. Norwegian King Crabs are as epic and delicious as it gets—perfect for a party—but we do also offer leg clusters that are much easier and quicker to prepare, ready to eat with just fifteen minutes of steaming.

It’s looking like we’re heading into the very last week of Chilean Black Winter truffle season, but even if you miss out on the fresh supply, don’t forget that we’re well-stocked on frozen truffles from the season’s peak.

Ibérico & Black Trumpet Soba

As summer begins hinting towards the fall, our catalog’s most macabre mushroom comes into season: Black Trumpets, AKA the Horn of Plenty, AKA Trumpets of the Dead. Their mysteriously brutalist reputation is reinforced by their distinct, smoky aroma, often compared to black truffles.

Amazing on their own, Black Trumpets are also an incredible secret weapon for sauces, enlivening their complexity while imbuing their color with an otherworldly allure as well.

Here, alongside freshly shaved truffles and one of our favorite cuts of Jersey-raised Puro Alentejano Ibérico pork, they elevate an umami-rich broth to epic proportions, making for a rich, nutty, earthy Soba dish that we’ll be leaning toward more and more as the days get shorter.

Swipe for a Black Trumpet solo shot 👉

Roasted Golden Chicken Leg with Saskatchewan Chanterelles

Feasting on 100% organic yellow corn and ranging freely for more than twice as long as mass-market chickens, these birds brilliantly exude the spoils of their rearing. Our partners have been breeding and raising this lineage of Golden Chickens for decades, each generation upholding and refining the traits that distinguish them.

This has become our go-to for any chicken recipe, and when Saskatchewan Chanterelles are in season, the mixture of sweetness and earthiness from these exceptional mushrooms plays off the centerpiece marvelously.

Hawaiian Hearts of Palm with Maine Bafun Uni and Trout Roe

A rare dish that fuses fresh ingredients from truly opposite corners of the country, this one gets it crisp, sweet foundation from Hawaiian Hearts of Palm and its brisk, umami-rich top-end from Maine Bafun Uni—just back in season this week. 

Maine Sea Urchins are close relatives to the Hokkaido Sea Urchins found off the shores of Japan’s northernmost prefecture. In Japanese cuisine, Uni is so prized that the vast majority of Maine’s production is exported to Toyosu Market each week. Fortunately, before this happens, we reserve a portion of the finest trays to be kept stateside.

Blue Crystal Prawn Crudo with Murasaki Uni & Green Finger Lime

With the heat back with a vengeance this week, we’ve been enjoying brightness and briskness as much as ever. These sushi-grade Blue Crystal Prawns come from the lagoons surrounding New Caledonia, and the Murasaki Uni is another crisp catch from the Pacific. Murasaki is the more delicate, floral, and tropically fruity of the primary Uni varieties, making it especially wonderful with sweet, raw shellfish. 

Finally, adorned here like pearls of caviar, we have Emerald Green Finger Lime from California, adding even more pop and shimmer to this invigorating dish.

Chirashi with A5 Wagyu, Ikura, and Platinum Osetra Caviar 

When serving any of our A5 Wagyu cuts from Japan, we often opt for something simple that lets the centerpiece shine. Chirashi is a perfect example—exquisite ingredients thoughtfully arranged atop a bed of sushi rice. On the top side of the plate we have a rolled omelette with white soy cured roe from wild King Salmon (Ikura), and on the bottom we have Platinum Osetra caviar. The caviar and roe both add splashes of brightness, and everything imbues the rice with scrumptious complexity.

Right now, we have A5 from the Kagoshima and Miyazaki prefectures. Both are outstanding, with Kagoshima known for its even marbling and depth of flavor, and Miyazaki for its soft texture and bright red color.

French Bread Slice with Matsutake Mushroom 

Matsutakes are back in season, and we’re thrilled to make the most of it. With an intense, spicy character reminiscent of pine, they deliver an intoxicating aroma and perfect texture, with defined firmness and super satisfying snap that goes especially well as a finely grated finishing touch, as shown here.

Though loved round the world, Matsutakes have an especially esteems history in Japan, where they were consumed only by members of the Imperial Court as recently as the seventeenth century. Sadly, Japan’s own production of these mushrooms has sharply declined over the last serval decades, largely due to the proliferation of the pine-killing nematode—Bursaphelenchus xylophilus. 

Though much Matsutake production elsewhere in the world makes its way back to the Japanese market, we are thrilled to keep some of the finest domestically foraged examples here at home.

Bafun Uni and Matsutake Don with Hand Polished Rice and Rye Shoyu

Inspired by Japanese cuisine and brought to life with American ingredients, this dish is a celebration of September. We’ve recently sung the praises of Maine Bafun Uni and wild Oregon Matsutake mushrooms, and they’re combined here to stunning effect—saline umami from the Uni, earthy spice from the Matsutake, complexity from the Rye Shoyu, comfort from the rice foundation. Garnished with roasted seaweed, this is a triumphant way to showcase some of the season’s most stunning ingredients—all available online now.

A5 Wagyu Checkerboard with Nitrogen Frozen Périgord Truffles & Siberian Sturgeon Caviar

Truffles, Wagyu and Caviar—there might not be a better trio of ingredients for showcasing what we’re all about. This simple presentation is made with true A5 from Japan, nitrogen-frozen Chilean Black Winter Truffles from the peak of this past season, and perhaps our most classic caviar, harvested from Siberian Sturgeon.

Elite and elusive as all of these ingredients are, it’s incredible how simply an astonishing dish can come together once you have them on hand. A5 Wagyu is best minimally cooked with just a quick sear to the exterior, the truffle is just thinly shaved, and the caviar is dolloped on top at the end. 

If ever needing something quick and easy that’s nowhere close to a compromise on quality—this is the ticket.

Roasted Golden Chicken with Herbed Dumplings & Amber Kaluga Caviar

No matter what the recipe, our Pennsylvania-raised Golden Chicken elevates it. Already starting off with such an envious shade, they go on to caramelize marvelously as well, with incredible texture and depth of flavor.

With herbed dumplings and a schmaltzy base sauce, this is a wonderful comfort dish that gets a bright finishing touch with caviar.

Roasted Duck with Burgundy Truffles & Lobster Mushrooms 

With summer winding down to fall, we’re blessed with a wide range of gorgeous mushrooms and ample ways to make the most of them. Here, we have fresh Burgundy Truffles, finally flourishing, alongside Lobster Mushrooms, which have had an incredible summer and will not be available much longer. 

Duck is an incredible foundation for the sweet, earthy, complex overtones provided by these mushrooms. Gorgeously succulent and with plenty of good fat for the other ingredients to bind to, any of our Duck offerings make for a fantastic focal point.

Tempura Fried Matsutake with Sansho Chili Aioli & Yuzu Kosho

You’ve seen how lovely these wild Matsutake mushrooms are when kept raw and thinly sliced, but because of their firm and snappy texture, they also stand up beautifully to frying. Here, a simple coating gives way to a meaty interior, while spicy aioli with zesty, vivacious Yuzu Kosho makes each bite a top-to-bottom delight.

Just like the Matsutakes at the heart of this dish, Yuzu Kosho is a prized piece of Japanese cuisine. Decadently floral, tart, and aromatic, the scent of Yuzu is so potent that it is cherished in Japan not only for its culinary value, but also as a perfume or bathing oil, depending on the occasion. In this spice medley, its zest and juice is combined with fermented green chiles that infuse any dish with complex vitality.

Matsutakes & Green Yuzu Kosho are both available online now.

Hamachi Sushi Bomb with fresh Japanese Wasabi & Siberian Sturgeon Caviar

Crown Toro Hamachi is an exquisite, sustainably sea-farmed fish from Uwajima, Japan. With a naturally smooth, buttery texture and delicate flavor, it’s prized for all sushi and sashimi applications. 

Here, the loin of the fish is garnished with top-notch wasabi and a dollop of Baerii caviar. This Green Stem wasabi has quickly became a favorite of ours, with ample sweetness and creamy texture to offset its characteristically bright green flavor and piquancy.

Spider Crab Smørrebrød

Found all over the world, Spider Crabs are a sustainable and incredibly tasty catch, with sweeter meat than many more commonly consumed crustaceans. Ours are flash-frozen right on the boat, retaining as much saline freshness and juicy texture as possible in an extremely practical and easy to use format.

Laid over a slice of rye bread with whipped crème fraîche, trout roe, chives, and lemon zest, this simple dish is a wonderful introduction to an underrated crab.

King Crab, Burgundy Truffle, Galangal and Thai Lime

King Crab is one of our favorite indulgences, so we’re thankful to currently have a few variations of it in stock. The most approachable are certainly our raw, frozen leg clusters from the Antarctic waters off the coast of southern Chile. Sweet, briskly briny, and succulent, their cold habitat equips them with an incredibly clean flavor and a wonderfully generous yield of meat per cluster.

Easy and forgiving to prepare, we’re keeping them simple here, adorned with peak-season Burgundy Truffles, lime, and galangal.

Right now, Burgundies are the best they’ve been so far this year, thanks to a much-needed rainy spell after a long drought. Well-hydrated truffles are always more aromatic, and we’re thrilled to see them coming into their own for the Fall.

Finger Limes

Native to southeast Queensland and New South Wales, Australia, Finger Limes are among our favorite rare fruits. We have both red and green varieties, with the red coming from Florida and the green from California. Their pulp is prized for its caviar-like texture—an amazing addition to any dish needing a little extra pop and shimmer. 

Both are bright, invigorating, and—unsurprisingly—citrusy. While both colors are beautiful, the Greens are a little more crisp and focused, while the Reds are more complex, often described as a juicy synergy of lemon, lime, and grapefruit altogether.

A5 Miyazaki Ribeye with Matsutake, Puffed Rice, and Chimichurri

No place has revered Matsutake mushrooms as long as Japan, so here we’re placing them alongside an elite Japanese centerpiece: A5 Wagyu from the Miyazaki Prefecture.

Only ~400 farmers raise cattle in the Miyazaki Prefecture, with a stunningly low farmer to cow ratio, ensuring that every animal receives the attention and respect required to raise the world’s finest Wagyu. Mostly fed wheat and corn, meat from this region is known for its bright red color, soft texture, and density of flavor. 

Here, the Wagyu is prepared with nothing but a quick sear and flecks of sea salt. The chimichurri adds fantastic vitality to the meat as well as the firm, spicy Matsutake, and the whole dish gets a refreshing pop of texture from the puffed rice.

White Truffle Bucatini

They’re back.

White Truffles are one of our most eagerly anticipated arrivals each year, in season for just a few fleeting weeks straddling fall and winter. Their flavor profile eludes easy summary: garlicky, rustic, and funky, reminiscent of exquisite cheese, with a caramelized nutty sweetness that melts marvelously into fat.

Unlike heftier truffle varieties, White Truffles should always be enjoyed raw, shaved directly onto a warm dish. This pasta, with nothing but a simple butter sauce, binds beautifully with the truffles, transforming it into an explosively aromatic and occasion-worthy meal.

Matsutake Toast with Golden Osetra & Red Shiso

Not all mushrooms are firm and flavorful enough to be the baseline for a simple toast, but Matsutakes are up to the task. With a spicy, foresty fragrance that’s earned them the alternate moniker of Pine Mushrooms, they are a powerful counterpoint to the brisk vibrancy of caviar, and their piquant notes of cinnamon are further reinforced here with fresh red shiso.

Ruby Red Carabinero Crudo & Red Finger Lime with Golden Osetra Caviar

Red on red: here we have Carabinero Prawns, caught off the coast of Huelva, Spain and flash frozen to retain all of their salty brightness and succulence, dolloped with the caviar-like pulp of Red Finger Limes for extra zip and vibrancy. Finished with just a bit of true caviar—Golden Osetra—this dish is a perfect choice for those in denial about the shortening sunlight and chilly temperatures of autumn.

All of these ingredients are in stock and poised to transport you to a far brighter place 😎

White Truffle Risotto

One of our favorite fall dishes, and one that we always eagerly anticipate as soon as White Truffles are back in season. There is hardly a better canvas for these explosively fragrant truffles than the cozy, creamy foundation of excellent risotto. 

Unlike heftier truffle varieties, White Truffles should always be enjoyed raw, shaved directly into a finished dish while still warm. Just this little bit of radiant heat is all it takes to unlock an abundance of garlicky allium aromatics and nutty sweetness.

Next Level Steak Frites: A5 Miyazaki Ribeye with Golden Osetra, Maine Bafun Uni, and Shoestring Potatoes

There are few things we love more than epic renditions of classic dishes, and anything with A5 Japanese Wagyu as its centerpiece guarantees to deliver. 

Differences in historical breeding practices, climate, diet, and farming techniques allow different prefectures’ Wagyu to evoke their terroir as assertively as wine does its appellation. In all cases, it is downright spectacular—sweet, complex, and as satiating for the spirit as the stomach. The cows in the Miyazaki prefecture, mostly fed wheat and corn, have an especially vibrant color, soft texture, and density of flavor.

Combined with crispy shoestring potatoes, the supple steak is especially luxurious, and while other variations on this dish may contain various condiments, ours gets its additional pops of brightness and texture from the brisk duo of caviar and Uni.
